snippet.textDisplay:
Terrible video.
You've made a mess out of deployment strategy; processes in VMs vs. containers. into the whole mess you've added a software architecture decision which is monolithic vs micro-services.
Just to be clean - you can have a microservice or SOA architecture while running processes inside VMs (valid and common strategy).
Kube is one way to do containers in production environments, the are lots of other container orchestrators widely used in production environments.

In addition - the kube nodes probably run on a... VM :D

snippet.textDisplay: @linus, you are absolutely wrong on this one. First of all, Netflix is not using docker containers for production (check with their team, I talked with them about this around 1 year ago), but only for development. Second, you are making the following assumption "microservices=docker containers", which is absolutely wrong. Many/most of microservices run in VMs, small, medium, etc. AWS ASGs (or Azure/GCP respective solutions) allow you to deploy your "microservices" in small VMs in a matter of minutes or seconds, depending on the size of AMI/"disk image". Hence your argument is absolutely wrong, and it seems to be just to back up your sponsor's message. As a matter of fact, AWS Lambdas, FaaS (Functions as a Service) are not using docker containers, but micro VMs instead, e.g. 1vCPU + 128 MB RAM. Please check the firecracker project (https://firecracker-microvm.github.io/). Using Docker containers outside of App tier is a "huge pain", as of networking and data persistence challenges. I like your channels, but please do not spread absolutely false information. Have a good one and take care!
